  "doc": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Every token in an LLM prompt is processed by the model, which costs both time and money. When you send the same large system prompt — with thousands of tokens of instructions, examples, or retrieved context — on every API call, you pay for it in full each time. Prompt caching lets the provider retain the KV-cache state of the shared prefix and reuse it across requests, so you only pay to process those tokens once."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "image",
        "attrs": {
          "src": "data:image/svg+xml;base64,",
          "alt": "Prompt caching comparison: three requests without caching bill the system prompt in full each time; with caching, requests 2 and 3 get a ~10% rate on the cached prefix. Shows Anthropic explicit cache_control and OpenAI automatic caching API patterns."
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "How Caching Works"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "When a request arrives, the provider checks whether the leading tokens match a cached prefix. If they do, the attention key-value tensors for those positions are already in GPU memory — the model only computes attention for the new (uncached) suffix. From the API perspective, cached tokens appear in "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "usage"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " as a separate counter and are billed at a discounted rate."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "Anthropic"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": ": you mark explicit cache breakpoints with "
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "code"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "\"cache_control\": {\"type\": \"ephemeral\"}"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": ". Cached tokens cost ~10% of the normal input rate. Cache entries expire after 5 minutes of disuse. Minimum cacheable block: 1024 tokens."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "OpenAI"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": ": caching is fully automatic for prompts whose prefix exceeds 1024 tokens. No special parameters needed. Cached tokens receive a 50% discount. The cache is keyed on the exact text of the prefix, so even a single character change invalidates it."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Anthropic Prompt Caching"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Mark the end of the section you want cached with "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "cache_control"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ". Everything up to and including that block is the cached prefix. Everything after it (and the new user message) is processed fresh each turn."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import anthropic\n\nclient = anthropic.Anthropic()\n\nLONG_SYSTEM_PROMPT = \"\"\"You are a senior code reviewer...\n[... 4000+ tokens of detailed instructions and examples ...]\n\"\"\"\n\ndef review_code(user_code: str) -> str:\n    response = client.messages.create(\n        model=\"claude-opus-4-5\",\n        max_tokens=1024,\n        system=[\n            {\n                \"type\": \"text\",\n                \"text\": LONG_SYSTEM_PROMPT,\n                \"cache_control\": {\"type\": \"ephemeral\"},  # cache this block\n            }\n        ],\n        messages=[{\"role\": \"user\", \"content\": f\"Review:\\n{user_code}\"}],\n    )\n\n    usage = response.usage\n    print(f\"Input tokens:   {usage.input_tokens}\")\n    print(f\"Cache write:    {usage.cache_creation_input_tokens}\")\n    print(f\"Cache read:     {usage.cache_read_input_tokens}\")\n    # On first call: cache_creation_input_tokens ≈ 4000, cache_read = 0\n    # On subsequent calls: cache_read ≈ 4000, cache_creation = 0\n\n    return response.content[0].text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "You can place up to four "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "cache_control"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " breakpoints in a single request. This is useful for caching progressively: a fixed system prompt, a set of retrieved documents, and a multi-turn conversation history can each be their own cached layer."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "# RAG with two cached layers: system prompt + retrieved docs\nresponse = client.messages.create(\n    model=\"claude-opus-4-5\",\n    max_tokens=512,\n    system=[\n        # Layer 1: static instructions (cached longest)\n        {\n            \"type\": \"text\",\n            \"text\": SYSTEM_INSTRUCTIONS,\n            \"cache_control\": {\"type\": \"ephemeral\"},\n        },\n        # Layer 2: retrieved context for this query (may change per session)\n        {\n            \"type\": \"text\",\n            \"text\": \"\\n\".join(retrieved_docs),\n            \"cache_control\": {\"type\": \"ephemeral\"},\n        },\n    ],\n    messages=[{\"role\": \"user\", \"content\": question}],\n)"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "OpenAI Automatic Caching"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "OpenAI caches the longest matching prefix automatically. No API changes are needed — just ensure your high-token-count content comes first in the message list and remains stable across requests."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "from openai import OpenAI\n\nclient = OpenAI()\n\nSYSTEM_PROMPT = \"...\"  # ≥ 1024 tokens for caching to engage\n\ndef ask(user_message: str) -> str:\n    response = client.chat.completions.create(\n        model=\"gpt-4o\",\n        messages=[\n            {\"role\": \"system\", \"content\": SYSTEM_PROMPT},\n            {\"role\": \"user\", \"content\": user_message},\n        ],\n    )\n\n    details = response.usage.prompt_tokens_details\n    print(f\"Total prompt tokens: {response.usage.prompt_tokens}\")\n    print(f\"Cached tokens:       {details.cached_tokens}\")\n    # On a cache hit, cached_tokens ≈ len(SYSTEM_PROMPT tokens)\n    # Cached tokens billed at 50% of normal input rate\n\n    return response.choices[0].message.content"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "blockquote",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "text",
                "marks": [
                  {
                    "type": "bold"
                  }
                ],
                "text": "Cache key stability"
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": ": any change to the cached prefix — including whitespace — creates a cache miss. Put dynamic content (user messages, per-request IDs) after the stable prefix, never before it."
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Multi-Turn Conversation Caching"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "In a chat session, each turn appends a new message while all previous turns remain constant. By marking the conversation history as cached, you avoid reprocessing the entire history on each turn."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import anthropic\n\nclient = anthropic.Anthropic()\n\nclass CachedChatSession:\n    def __init__(self, system_prompt: str):\n        self.system = [\n            {\"type\": \"text\", \"text\": system_prompt,\n             \"cache_control\": {\"type\": \"ephemeral\"}}\n        ]\n        self.history: list[dict] = []\n\n    def send(self, user_message: str) -> str:\n        self.history.append({\"role\": \"user\", \"content\": user_message})\n\n        # Mark everything except the last user message as cached.\n        # Build messages list: older turns marked for caching.\n        messages = []\n        for i, msg in enumerate(self.history[:-1]):\n            if i == len(self.history) - 2:  # last assistant turn\n                content = msg[\"content\"]\n                if isinstance(content, str):\n                    content = [{\"type\": \"text\", \"text\": content,\n                                \"cache_control\": {\"type\": \"ephemeral\"}}]\n                messages.append({\"role\": msg[\"role\"], \"content\": content})\n            else:\n                messages.append(msg)\n        messages.append(self.history[-1])  # new user message, not cached\n\n        response = client.messages.create(\n            model=\"claude-opus-4-5\",\n            max_tokens=512,\n            system=self.system,\n            messages=messages,\n        )\n\n        reply = response.content[0].text\n        self.history.append({\"role\": \"assistant\", \"content\": reply})\n        return reply"
          }
        ]
      },
